Class Scenario<I,O>

java.lang.Object
scenarios.Scenario<I,O>
Type Parameters:
I - the input type
O - the output type
public class Scenario<I,O> extends Object
Represents an input-output scenario for a generated function.

A Scenario is used to define a specific example of an input and its corresponding expected output for a generated function. This is useful for both guiding the function generation and for testing the function's correctness. Scenarios help ensure that the generated function behaves as expected across a variety of cases, including normal, edge, and error cases.

Scenarios are a way to train a function generator with examples of input-output pairs to demonstrate how the generated function should behave in different situations.

Example usage:

 
 // Create scenarios with descriptions
 Scenario<String, String> allBooksScenario = new Scenario<>(
     "I want to see all books",
     "SELECT * FROM books",
     "When the user asks to see all books, generate a SELECT query for the books table."
 );
 
 Scenario<String, String> authorScenario = new Scenario<>(
     "I want to find books written by George Orwell",
     "SELECT * FROM books WHERE author = 'George Orwell'",
     "When the user requests books by a specific author, generate a SELECT query with a WHERE clause for the author."
 );
 
 Scenario<String, String> yearScenario = new Scenario<>(
     "Show me books published in 1984",
     "SELECT * FROM books WHERE year = 1984",
     "When the user requests books published in a specific year, generate a SELECT query with a WHERE clause for the publication year."
 );
 
 Scenario<String, String> titleKeywordScenario = new Scenario<>(
     "Find books with the word Harry in the title",
     "SELECT * FROM books WHERE title LIKE '%Harry%'",
     "When the user requests books with a keyword in the title, generate a SELECT query with a LIKE clause."
 );
 
 System.out.println(allBooksScenario);
 // Output: Input: I want to see all books, Expected Output: SELECT * FROM books, Description: When the user asks to see all books, generate a SELECT query for the books table.

Best Practices:

  • Include scenarios that cover normal, edge, and error cases to ensure robustness of the generated function.
  • Provide a meaningful description for each scenario to improve clarity and help understand its purpose.
  • Use scenarios with diverse inputs to enhance the ability of the generated function to generalize its behavior.
